    <mxCell id="k10cap" parent="1" style="text;html=1;align=left;fontSize=9;" value="2 M-slices × 2 N-slices = &lt;b&gt;4 patches scattered&lt;/b&gt; across the warp tile&#10;(one per subtile, all owned by the SAME thread = 128 results)" vertex="1"><mxGeometry x="680" y="360" width="360" height="44" as="geometry" /></mxCell>
    <mxCell id="note" parent="1" style="rounded=1;whiteSpace=wrap;html=1;fillColor=#fef3c7;strokeColor=#b45309;fontSize=10;align=left;verticalAlign=middle;spacingLeft=10;spacingRight=10;" value="&lt;b&gt;The spatial difference:&lt;/b&gt; kernel 6's thread takes one M-slice and one N-slice from SMEM and fills a single 8×8 block of C. Kernel 10's thread grabs &lt;b&gt;WMITER M-slices and WNITER N-slices&lt;/b&gt; spaced WSUBM/WSUBN apart, then forms &lt;b&gt;every M-slice × N-slice combination&lt;/b&gt; — so its results are 4 small patches scattered across the warp tile, not one block. Loading those slices once per dotIdx and reusing them across all 4 patches is what raises arithmetic intensity." vertex="1"><mxGeometry x="20" y="470" width="1080" height="56" as="geometry" /></mxCell>
